# HLS Stream Debugger

Single-page React app that parses and plays HLS streams in the browser. Deployed as a static site on Vercel.

## Stack

- Vite 8 + React 19 + TypeScript (strict)
- `hls.js` for MSE playback (Chrome, Firefox, Edge, Android)
- Native `<video>` HLS for Safari / iOS
- `m3u8-parser` for manifest parsing
- No backend — all fetching happens client-side

## File layout

- `src/lib/types.ts` — shared TypeScript interfaces (`ParsedManifest`, `Variant`, `MediaTrack`, `RuntimeTrack`)
- `src/lib/parseManifest.ts` — wraps `m3u8-parser`, returns typed `ParsedManifest`
- `src/lib/resolveUrl.ts` — resolves relative playlist URIs against base URL
- `src/components/` — one file per UI panel (UrlForm, VideoPanel, RenditionList, AudioTrackList, CaptionTrackList, CollapsiblePanel)
- `src/App.tsx` — all state, HLS lifecycle, and layout live here
- `src/index.css` — single global stylesheet using CSS custom properties

## Key patterns

- **Dual playback path**: `Hls.isSupported()` → hls.js; else `video.canPlayType('application/vnd.apple.mpegurl')` → native. Always check `isNativeRef` before calling hls.js APIs.
- **Rendition switching**: loads the variant's media playlist URL directly (destroys and recreates the player).
- **Track switching**: `hls.audioTrack` / `hls.subtitleTrack` on MSE; `video.audioTracks` / `video.textTracks` on native Safari.
- **CORS**: stream servers must send `Access-Control-Allow-Origin`. Surface a clear error message when fetch fails with TypeError.

## Deployment

- `vercel.json` rewrites all routes to `index.html`
- Build: `npm run build` → `dist/`
- Node 22 (pinned in `.nvmrc`)
